    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-06-12T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-06-12T07:00:00-05:00" n="349"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.84/101: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Addis Ababa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-06-12T15:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 12, 1936—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:44 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>418. Last paragraph Department’s 270, June 9. None of the chiefs of mission here
                    used the title of “Viceroy” in addressing Badoglio. Graziani has never called
                    himself even Acting Viceroy but only Governor General ad interim. I have been
                    careful to refer to him befittingly as “Commander in Chief” thus taking
                    cognizance of his presence merely as the highest authority in military
                    occupation and in no sense implying recognition of Italian sovereignty.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
